for the prediction of release rates of radionuclides from fuel especially in contact with water after an accident remain limited relatively little is known about fuel corrosion and radionuclide release under the extreme chemical radiation and thermal conditions during and subsequent to a nuclear accident we review the current understanding of nuclear fuel interactions with the environment including studies over the relatively narrow range of geochemical hydrological and radiation environments relevant to geological repository performance and discuss priorities for research needed to develop future predictive models download html+ go to site external http www sciencemag org content 3 topics water search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publication news stanford experts look at lessons learned from japan crisis march 12 2012 cisac in the news publications of interest behind russia and iran's nuclear reactor dispute pavel podvig the bulletin online 2007 html+ cover international regime of fresh fuel supply and spent fuel disposal chaim braun michael m may nonproliferation review vol 13 1 2006 pdf+ cover the key role of the back end in the nuclear fuel cycle thomas isaacs charles mccombie daedalus vol vol 2 2010 pdf+ cover spent nuclear fuel jordi bruno rodney c ewing elements vol 2 2006 pdf+ support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4581 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
